I have completed the task. 

I proposed a new, parsimonious single-mechanism cognitive hypothesis based on the **entropy of the run-length distribution**. 

Instead of relying on alternating cues or penalizing runs locally, this hypothesis states that people perceive sequences as random if they contain an unpredictable, diverse mix of short and long streaks. It naturally addresses both streak-aversion (a sequence with 1 long streak has a single run length and an entropy of 0) and over-alternation aversion (a sequence like HTHTHT has all runs of length 1, also an entropy of 0), while directly responding to the `beta_max_run_norm` critique by valuing diversity rather than strictly penalizing the absolute length of the maximum streak. 

Both `hypothesis.md` and `candidate.py` have been written to the target directory and pass the structural self-checks.
